most%20talented%20experimental%20physicist%20he%20had%20ever%20known%2C%20and%20that%20she%20would%20make%20any%20laboratory%20shine.%26quot%3B%20%3Cbr%3E%3Cbr%3EOppenheimer%20himself%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2Fbooks%2Fedition%2FMadame_Wu_Chien_shiung_The_First_Lady_Of%2Fr30GCwAAQBAJ%3Fhl%3Den%26gbpv%3D1%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ereportedly%3C%2Fa%3E%20said%2C%20%26quot%3BGo%20invite%20Ms.%20Wu%20%E2%80%94%20she%20knows%20everything%20about%20the%20absorption%20cross%20section%20of%20neutrons.%26quot%3B%20(According%20to%20her%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Flifestyle%2F2021%2F12%2F13%2Fchien-shiung-wu-biography-physics-grandmother%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egranddaughter%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20Wu%20called%20him%20%26quot%3BOppie%2C%26quot%3B%20while%20Oppenheimer%20called%20her%20%26quot%3BJiejie%2C%26quot%3B%20a%20term%20of%20endearment%20meaning%20%26quot%3Belder%20sister%26quot%3B%20in%20Chinese.)%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20his%20autobiography%2C%20prominent%20Italian%20physicist%20Emilio%20Segr%C3%A8%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcosmosmagazine.com%2Fscience%2Fphysics%2Fforgotten-women-in-science-chien-shiung-wu%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecompared%3C%2Fa%3E%20Wu%20to%20her%20heroine%20Marie%20Curie%2C%20but%20said%20Wu%20was%20more%20%26quot%3Bworldly%2C%20elegant%2C%20and%20witty.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20sexism%20and%20anti-Asian%20racism%20that%20only%20intensified%20after%20the%20Pearl%20Harbor%20attack%20prevented%20Wu%20from%20securing%20a%20good%20academic%20job.%20She%20married%20her%20colleague%20Luke%20Yuan%20and%20moved%20to%20the%20East%20Coast.%20Wu%20eventually%20accepted%20a%20job%20at%20Princeton%20University%2C%20becoming%20the%20first%20female%20faculty%20member%20in%20the%20history%20of%20its%20physics%20department.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Chien-Shiung%20Wu%20(1912-1997)%2C%20professor%20of%20physics%20at%20Columbia%20University%2C%20shown%20with%20a%20%26quot%3BDr.%20Brode%26quot%3B%20(probably%20Wallace%20Brode)%20and%20a%20group%20of%20Science%20Talent%20Search%20winners%2C%201958%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64c00f29ed4f460019635ffd%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221500%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EChien-Shiung%20Wu%20shown%20with%20a%20%26quot%3BDr.%20Brode%26quot%3B%20(probably%20Wallace%20Brode)%20and%20a%20group%20of%20Science%20Talent%20Search%20winners%2C%201958.%3Cp%3ESmithsonian%20Institution%20Archives%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Ch2%3EThe%20Manhattan%20Project%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20March%201944%2C%20Wu%20was%20recruited%20to%20the%20Manhattan%20Project%20at%20Columbia%20University%2C%20where%20she%20helped%20develop%20the%20process%20for%20separating%20uranium%20%E2%80%94%20crucial%20to%20producing%20enriched%20uranium%20to%20fuel%20the%20atomic%20bombs%20at%20the%20Oak%20Ridge%20facility.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWu%20also%20helped%20solve%20a%20problem%20involving%20an%20isotope's%20chain%20reaction%20that%20stumped%20the%20other%20scientists.%20Enrico%20Fermi%2C%20who%20became%20the%20associate%20director%20of%20the%20laboratory%20at%20Los%20Alamos%20in%201944%2C%20was%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22http%3A%2F%2Fcwp.library.ucla.edu%2Farticles%2Fwuobit.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ereportedly%3C%2Fa%3E%20told%20to%20%26quot%3Bask%20Ms.%20Wu.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20turned%20out%20that%20Wu's%20graduate%20school%20thesis%20had%20been%20on%20the%20isotopes%20in%20question%2C%20which%20were%20instrumental%20in%20solving%20the%20issue.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ELike%20many%20other%20scientists%20involved%20in%20the%20project%2C%20Wu%20later%20distanced%20herself%20from%20the%20Manhattan%20Project%20due%20to%20its%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.insider.com%2Fnuclear-weapon-stre